 <> =E2=80=9Ccentral bank digital currency=E2=80=9D annoying. =0ADollarsare=
 a central bank digital currency. The Federal Reserve issues dollars =0Ain =
the form of digital entries in thereserve accounts that banks keep at the F=
ed=0A <>. Your dollars consist of electronic entries in the ledger of some =
bank, not =0Athe Fed; your dollars are not exactly central bank digital cur=
rency. But your =0Abank has some dollars at the Fed, and those dollars are =
digital. They are =0Acentral bank digital currency.=0A=0AOf course ordinari=
ly when people say <> =E2=80=9Ccentral bank digital currency,=E2=80=9D or =
=0A=E2=80=9CCBDC,=E2=80=9Dthey mean something slightly different <>. They m=
ean that the Fed would =0Aissue dollars that (1) are on some blockchain and=
 (2) anyone =E2=80=94 not just a bank =0A=E2=80=94 can hold. In this struct=
ure, CBDC dollars would be liabilities of the Fed =0A(not of particular com=
mercial banks), and could be transferred freely on the =0Ablockchain betwee=
n banks, companies, individuals, etc.=0A=0ANow perhaps my annoyance is pett=
y. =E2=80=9CWidely available, non-fractional-reserve, =0Acentral bank-issue=
d, blockchain-based dollar=E2=80=9D is probably more descriptive than =0A=
=E2=80=9Ccentral bank digital currency,=E2=80=9D but it is unwieldy, and ev=
eryone involved in =0Acrypto monetary discussions understands what =E2=80=
=9Ccentral bank digital currency=E2=80=9D is =0Ashorthand for. If you areno=
t involved in crypto monetary discussions, it can be =0Amisleading =E2=80=
=94 =E2=80=9Cwait, Fed reservesare central bank digital currencies=3F=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=94 but =0Awhatever, you can figure it out.=0A=0AStill sometimes =
one wants to be a bit pedantic. This week I mentioned <> =0ADonald Trump=E2=
=80=99sexecutive order <> on crypto, which among other things prohibits =0A=
US agencies from taking =E2=80=9Cany action to establish, issue, or promote=
 CBDCs =0Awithin the jurisdiction of the United States or abroad.=E2=80=9D =
This is a plausible =0Apolicy choice: CBDCs have potential weird effects on=
 monetary policy, and =0Acrypto=E2=80=99s techno-libertarians oppose them o=
n techno-libertarian grounds. (The =0AFed could track your spending or seiz=
e your money, etc.) My impression is that =0Athe Fed was already pretty ske=
ptical of CBDCs anyway. (And some of Trump=E2=80=99s team =0Aareclose with =
Tether <>, which issues digital dollars, and perhaps don=E2=80=99t want =0A=
competition from the Fed.)=0A=0ABut! A reader emailed me to point out that =
there is some concern in the market =0Athat the executive orderprohibits ba=
nk reserves. After all, it prohibits CBDCs, =0Aand defines CBDCs as:=0A=0A =
=E2=80=9CCentral Bank Digital Currency=E2=80=9D means a form of digital mon=
ey or monetary =0Avalue, denominated in the national unit of account, that =
is a direct liability =0Aof the central bank.=0A=0ARight no that does seem =
to include bank reserves. Ehh I=E2=80=99m sure it=E2=80=99s fine.=0A=0A=0AE=
nron=3F=3F=0A=0ALast month, someone relaunched the Enron.com website and @E=
nron accounts on =0Asocial media. They were,I figured <>, kidding. For one =
thing, they said that =0A=E2=80=9CEnron=E2=80=9D now stands for Energy, Nur=
ture, Repentant, Opportunity and Nice, which =0Ais funny. Also the website =
included a disclaimer saying it was a parody.=0A=0ABut in 2025, what does i=
t mean to be =E2=80=9Ckidding=E2=80=9D=3F What is the difference between =
=0A=E2=80=9Ca parody=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ca meme=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ca f=
inancial product=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ca viable business=E2=80=9D=3F Are =
=0Aall the best businesses parodies of themselves=3F I am sure I do not kno=
w. Iwrote =0Aat the time <>:=0A=0AThings are different, standards are lower=
, and people are up for a bit more =0Afun. If you launched Enron Corp. on t=
he stock exchange today =E2=80=94 even without a =0Abusiness =E2=80=94 the =
stock would go up, because that is funny. =E2=80=9CSynonomous with =0Awillf=
ul corporate fraud and corruption=E2=80=9D is the sort of meme that, in 202=
4, is=0Avaluable. =E2=80=A6 =0A=0A=E2=80=9CThe information on the website i=
s First Amendment protected parody,=E2=80=9D says a =0Adisclaimer <>, =E2=
=80=9Crepresents performance art, and is for entertainment purposes =0Aonly=
,=E2=80=9D but these days you=E2=80=99d say that even if you actually were =
launching a =0Acrypto token, or a meme stock, or for that matter an energy =
company.=0A=0AAnyway here=E2=80=99s a Houston Chronicle article <> that is =
like =E2=80=9CEnron is sort of =0Akidding but also sort of not=E2=80=9D:=0A=
=0AIt=E2=80=99s not hard to see why skepticism runs high. Enron=E2=80=99s s=
ocial media feeds are =0Afilled with outlandish posts, including Impossible=
 claims about an egg-shaped =0Anuclear reactor capable of powering a home f=
or a decade. The company=E2=80=99s =0A28-year-old CEO, Connor Gaydos, also =
has a history with Birds Aren=E2=80=99t Real, the =0Ainternet=E2=80=99s fav=
orite satirical conspiracy theory from 2017.=0A=0ABut a subsidiary of Enron=
, Enron Energy Texas LLC, recently filed to become a =0ATexas retail electr=
ic provider. Gaining this designation would allow Enron to =0Asell electric=
ity plans to Texas consumers =E2=80=94 a move that, unlike the Enron Egg, =
=0Aat least has the appearance of sincerity=0A=0AGregory Forero, one of Enr=
on=E2=80=99s newly revealed executives and founder of a =0Alegitimate compa=
ny known as HGP Storage, submitted signed and notarized =0Aaffidavits attes=
ting to the company=E2=80=99s intent to become a bonafide energy =0Aprovide=
r. HGP develops utility-scale battery storage farms, a resource that has =
=0Agrown rapidly on the Texas grid in recent years.=0A=0AIn a Wednesday int=
erview, Forero again emphasized to the Chronicle that Enron =0Ais not a par=
ody or a publicity stunt. Residents may soon be able to choose =0AEnron as =
their power provider, he said.=0A=0A=E2=80=9CThe retail energy provider bus=
iness hasn't changed since deregulation,=E2=80=9D =0AForero said, referenci=
ng the break-up of Texas=E2=80=99 electricity market into three =0Aseparate=
 sectors in the early 2000s. =E2=80=9CIt's stagnant. The user experience fo=
r =0Aresidential is suboptimal. It's AOL dial-up technology, basically.=E2=
=80=9D=0A=0AOkay! On the one hand it is weird to launch a Texas retail elec=
tric power =0Acompany and choose, from all the possible names in the world,=
Enron. On the =0Aother hand, I mean, yes: These days Bad is Good, Actually,=
 and having a name =0Athat is synonymous withaccounting fraud <> and also m=
anipulating markets to =0Agouge retail customers and cause blackouts <> is =
probably good marketing. =E2=80=9COh =0Aman, I remember Enron being super e=
vil, I=E2=80=99d better sign up!=E2=80=9D=0A=0AOn the one hand, it is weird=
 to launch a real (=3F=3F=3F) retail power offering a =0Aweek after you lau=
nch a fake egg-shaped home nuclear reactor. On the other =0Ahand, has that =
not been Tesla=E2=80=99s whole schtick for years=3F Ithink a lot <> about =
=0Athe time in 2019 that Elon Muskannounced a rocket-powered flying Tesla <=
>. =0AThere are also real Teslas. It=E2=80=99s fine! Your business can be h=
alf real and half =0Ajokes, and you can grin coyly whenever anyone tries to=
 figure out which half is =0Awhich. Enron is back, in the literal(ish) sens=
e but also in the spiritual sense.=0A=0A=0AThings happen=0A=0A SoftBank <> =
in Talks to Invest Up to $25 Billion in OpenAI. Compute Exchange =0A<>. Deu=
tsche Bank <> chief says =E2=80=98nothing is off limits=E2=80=99 as profits=
 plunge. =0ABlackstone defends $80bndata centre investment <> as DeepSeek s=
hakes market. =0ABlackstone Set forNew York Office <> Comeback With Midtown=
 Tower. Goldman =0AVenture Buys $300 Million ofWarehouses <> From Blackston=
e. Fortress Targets $1 =0ABillion for LatestLitigation Finance Fund <>. Bla=
ckstone Turns to Canada=E2=80=99s =0AWealthy <> to Broaden BXPE=E2=80=99s R=
each. Major Penn Entertainment <> Shareholder =0ALaunches Proxy Fight. =E2=
=80=9CBarnes & Noble has become something of a gathering place =0Aforbook i=
nfluencers <>.=E2=80=9D Deutsche Bank has published a bunch of memes <> abo=
ut =0ADeepSeek.=0A=0AIf you'd like to get Money Stuff in handy email form, =
right in your inbox, =0Apleasesubscribe at this link <>. Or you can subscri=
be to Money Stuff and other =0Agreat Bloomberg newslettershere <>. Thanks!=
=0A=0A[1] I apologize for typing out the two different versions of this =E2=
=80=94 the long =0Aand short versions =E2=80=94 because I think that they a=
re identical in every material =0Arespect. =E2=80=9CYou make a bet on a sto=
ck, you tweet the bet, the bet works out and =0Ayou close out the bet,=E2=
=80=9D where the bet is long or short. But I should say that =0Asome people=
 seem to disagree with this: There is a popular view that short =0Aselling =
is inherently bad and therefore the short version is market =0Amanipulation=
, while the long version is fine.=0A=0A[2] This is oversimplified, and it=
=E2=80=99s of course quite common for your thesis to =0Abe right (or wrong)=
 and to lose (or make) money anyway for unrelated reasons =0Ayou weren=E2=
=80=99t thinking about, but you know what I mean.=0A=0A[3] This doesn=E2=80=
=99t necessarily mean that the stock price is what you said it =0Awould be =
worth in five years. It means that the stock=E2=80=99s price today equals w=
hat =0Ayou said it would be worth in five years, discounted at some rate th=
at reflects =0Athe risk of that prediction.=0A=0A[4] I have written about t=
his model of quickly taking profits from activist =0Ashorting before, inclu=
ding about Andrew Left <>: =E2=80=9CCitron is in this model a =0Aservice pr=
ovider to the market: It informs the market that Company X is a =0Afraud, t=
he market saves a lot of money (by not buying Company X at $100 =0Aanymore)=
, and Citron gets a reasonable cut of the money immediately. Citron is =0An=
ot a long-term investor that has to ride Company X all the way down, and it=
 =0Adoesn=E2=80=99t have to make 100% of its profits on any trade contingen=
t on being 100% =0Aright about Company X. In the long run, all of its profi=
ts are contingent on =0Abeing right enough about enough of its trades that =
people keep listening to it =0Aand prices keep going down.=E2=80=9D=0A=0A[5=
] This one is considerably less common, but it exists in the academic =0Ali=
terature <> and has been around for decades <>.=0A=0A[6] And some pump-and-=
dump trades: He was not *only* a short seller.=0A=0A[7] This is a very slig=
ht joke; you can still call them =E2=80=9Cprivate equity =0Afirms.=E2=80=9D=
 (Or =E2=80=9Csponsors.=E2=80=9D) But all they want to talk about these day=
s is private =0Acredit, so the more generic term seems more correct.=0A=0A=
